#!/bin/bash

curl -X POST "http://localhost:8000/generate-video" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{
    "title": "The Coffee Shop",
    "type": "story",
    "story": "There is a small coffee shop on the corner of our street. We used to go there every Sunday morning, the three of us — me, my best friend, and the person I thought was the love of my life. It was our place. The corner table by the window, the same order every time, the same easy laughter. I thought those mornings would never end. I was wrong. It started with small things I chose to ignore. A message notification she quickly turned face down. A reason why he could not make Sunday anymore. A look between them that lasted half a second too long. I told myself I was being paranoid. People who love you do not do that. Friends do not do that. So I pushed the feeling down and smiled through the coffee and the croissants and the easy laughter that no longer felt quite so easy. The truth came on a Tuesday. Not a Sunday, not at our corner table. It came in the form of a screenshot sent by someone who thought I already knew. A week of messages. Tender, secret, devastating. Every word a small detonation. I read them twice to make sure I understood what I was reading. I did. I sat with that knowledge for three days before I said anything. Three days of watching them both act completely normal. Smiling at me. Asking how my day was. Sitting across from me at dinner. I have never felt so alone in a room full of people who were supposed to be my people. When I finally confronted them, neither of them denied it. There was crying. There were apologies that felt more like relief than remorse. He said it just happened. She said she never meant to hurt me. I have spent a long time thinking about those words. Things do not just happen. You choose, moment after moment, to let them. And people who truly do not mean to hurt you stop before the hurt becomes catastrophic. They did not stop. What broke me most was not the betrayal itself. It was the ordinary moments that came after — realising how many of our memories I would now have to reexamine. Every time she had told me I was overthinking. Every time he had kissed me goodbye in the morning. The coffee shop. The corner table. The Sunday mornings I had believed were sacred. None of it was what I thought it was. I do not go to that coffee shop anymore. I drive past it sometimes and feel nothing, which is its own kind of healing I suppose. The people in your life are not always who you believe them to be. That is not a reason to stop trusting. It is a reason to pay closer attention to what people show you, not just what they tell you. Time has a way of making things clearer. I am grateful for that, even when the clarity is painful."
  }'